–Deceased","1189–1233":"1189–1233","1225–Male":"1225–Deceased","1235–1310":"1235–1310","1172–1208":"1172–1208","1175–1217":"1175–1217","before 1225":"before 1225","1187":"1187","1242":"1242","20 April 1208":"20 April 1208","1175":"1175","1172":"1172","1217":"1217","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","after 1217":"after 1217","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1233":"1233","1310":"1310","1189":"1189","1208":"1208","Hilton, Durham, England":"Hilton, Durham, England","Stokesley, Yorkshire, England":"Stokesley, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hilton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire):","habitational name from any of various places called Hilton (e.g. in Cambridgeshire, Derbyshire, Staffordshire, North Yorkshire, and Westmorland), most of which derive from Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some come from Old English <i>helde</i> ‘slope’ + <i>tūn</i>.","occasionally, as in the case of Ralph <i>filius Hilton</i> (Yorkshire 1219), perhaps from the personal name <i>Hilton</i>, itself a possible form of Norman <i>Hildun</i>, composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’ + <i>hūn</i> ‘bear cub’. Compare   Hilt  . This English surname is present in Ireland (mainly taken to Ulster in the early 17th century, though recorded earlier in Dublin)."],"variants":[{"name":"Hylton","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Hilton  ."]},{"name":"Hulton","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Hulton (Lancashire) or Hulton (Staffordshire), both from Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Hilton  ."]},{"name":"Hilt","meanings":["German: from a short form of   Hildebrand   or some other compound ancient Germanic name formed with <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’ as the first element. See   Hild  .","English (London): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hilte</i>, ultimately from ancient Germanic <i>Helto</i>, probably from <i>halith-</i> ‘hero’."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":28,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":37,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander de Hilton was born in 1187, in Hilton, Durham, England, his father, William de Hilton, was 15 and his mother, Beneta Tyson, was 12. He married Agnes de Verley before 1225. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1242, in his hometown, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1187–1242":"1187–1242","1205–Male":"1205–Surnud","1189–1233":"1189–1233","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1235–1310":"1235–1310","1172–1208":"1172–1208","1175–1217":"1175–1217","before 1225":"enne 1225","1187":"1187","1242":"1242","20 April 1208":"20. aprill 1208","1175":"1175","1172":"1172","1217":"1217","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","after 1217":"pärast 1217","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1233":"1233","1310":"1310","1189":"1189","1208":"1208","Hilton, Durham, England":"Hilton, Durham, England","Stokesley, Yorkshire, England":"Stokesley, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1187–1242":"1187–1242","1205–Male":"1205–Kuollut","1189–1233":"1189–1233","1225–Male":"1225–Kuollut","1235–1310":"1235–1310","1172–1208":"1172–1208","1175–1217":"1175–1217","before 1225":"ennen vuotta 1225","1187":"1187","1242":"1242","20 April 1208":"20. huhtikuuta 1208","1175":"1175","1172":"1172","1217":"1217","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","after 1217":"1217 jälkeen","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1233":"1233","1310":"1310","1189":"1189","1208":"1208","Hilton, Durham, England":"Hilton, Durham, England","Stokesley, Yorkshire, England":"Stokesley, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1187–1242":"1187–1242","1205–Male":"1205–Décédé","1189–1233":"1189–1233","1225–Male":"1225–Décédé","1235–1310":"1235–1310","1172–1208":"1172–1208","1175–1217":"1175–1217","bef